{
  "query": "How do long-term and temporary fishery closures compare in their effects on marine fish abundance?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on the available evidence, long-term fishery closures show more positive effects on marine fish abundance compared to temporary closures. Long-term closures (6-8 years) demonstrated higher abundance in 2 of 7 fish species in the Gulf of Maine and Bismark Sea (action 2655). In contrast, temporary closures showed no increase in fish biomass or abundance for cod in the Atlantic Ocean over nine years (action 2664), and no increase in invertebrate biomass at sites seasonally closed to fishing in the English Channel (action 2098). However, both temporary and long-term closures showed mixed or neutral results for some species - temporary closures had no effect on cod survival or condition (action 2664), while long-term closures showed either similar or lower abundance for certain species like monkfish and salmon (action 2655). The evidence suggests that longer protection periods may be necessary to see measurable increases in fish abundance, though responses vary by species.",
  "action_ids": [
    "2655",
    "2664",
    "2098",
    "3545"
  ]
}

