{
  "query": "What are the comparative effects on fish abundance of prohibiting all static fishing gear versus prohibiting only line fishing?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on available studies, there is limited but specific evidence on the comparative effects of prohibiting static fishing gear versus prohibiting line fishing on fish abundance. Prohibition of static fishing gear: One study in the Coral Sea found that areas closed to non-towed fishing gears had higher overall shark abundance when sampled with longlines compared to areas where commercial gillnets were permitted. Shark length was greater for two of five species/groups in these closed areas. Prohibition of line fishing: One study in the Indian Ocean found that prohibiting offshore line fishing and all other boat-based fishing resulted in higher abundances of four fish species that were over-exploited by line fishing compared to areas where boat-based line and spear fishing was permitted. The evidence suggests both types of prohibitions can have positive effects on fish abundance, but they target different aspects - static gear prohibition appears beneficial for shark populations, while line fishing prohibition helps recover species specifically over-exploited by line fishing.",
  "action_ids": [
    "2670",
