{
  "query": "What are the outcomes for fish populations when marine protected areas are managed with zonation systems that permit some fishing?",
  "relevant_summary": "Marine protected areas with zonation systems that permit some fishing show mixed outcomes for fish populations. Studies found that zones with higher protection levels (no-take/no-entry zones) generally had greater fish abundance, biomass, and species richness compared to partially fished zones within the same protected area. Site comparison studies across multiple regions (South Africa, Australia, Italy, Philippines) found that fish abundance and biomass varied with the level of restriction, with no-fishing zones having higher values than partially fished zones. Fish sizes were also larger in zones with greater protection restrictions. However, one study found that while abundance increased in no-entry zones compared to no-take and fished zones, the effects varied between fish feeding groups, zone protection level, and reef region. Fish behavior also showed positive responses in high-protection zones, with tagged reef fish remaining mainly in zones where all or nearly all fishing was prohibited for up to 20 years.",
  "action_ids": [
    "2674",
    "2230",
    "2681"
  ]
}

