{
  "query": "How does the effectiveness of prohibiting mobile bottom fishing gear vary between the North Atlantic and other regions like the Mediterranean or Indian Ocean?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on studies examining the effectiveness of prohibiting mobile bottom fishing gears across different regions, the following patterns emerge:\n\nNorth Atlantic Ocean (Canada): Research shows mixed effectiveness. One study found that after 14 years of closure to bottom trawling, recruitment of young red mullet had increased. However, another study found that closing an area to bottom trawling did not increase recruitment or survival of young haddock seven years after closure compared to trawled areas.\n\nMediterranean Sea: Studies in the Mediterranean show generally positive results. After a 14-year closure to bottom trawling, adult red mullet showed increased biomass and larger sizes. Additionally, after the closure of an area to bottom trawling, recruitment of young red mullet had increased, though this was not consistent across all fish groups.\n\nIndian Ocean (Tasmania, Kenya): Research from the Indian Ocean region shows variable results depending on habitat type and individual fish groups. Studies found that closing areas to towed bottom gears for 3-14 years had effects on fish size that varied between individual fish groups and with habitat type, compared to fished areas.\n\nOverall Effectiveness: The effectiveness of bottom fishing gear prohibitions appears to be highly variable across regions and is influenced by several factors including the duration of closure (ranging from 3 to 15 years in these studies), habitat type, and specific fish species or groups studied.",
  "action_ids": [
    "2673",
    "2654",
    "2099"
  ]
}

