{
  "query": "How do separator trawls and topless trawls compare in their effectiveness at reducing unwanted fish catch?",
  "relevant_summary": "Both separator trawls and topless trawls have shown effectiveness at reducing unwanted fish catch, though they work through different mechanisms and have been studied to varying extents. Separator trawls were examined in two studies - one in the North Sea found they separated unwanted cod from target species into a lower codend with larger mesh sizes that allowed more smaller cod to escape, while another in the Atlantic Ocean found they caught less of one of two unwanted fish species when fitted with square-mesh escape panels. Topless trawls were studied more extensively with four studies across the North Sea, Gulf of Maine, and Baltic Sea regions. These studies showed mixed but generally positive results - two studies found they reduced unwanted Atlantic cod catch and discards of commercial species, one found they reduced catches of larger but not smaller haddock and larger cod only in one case, and another found discarded catches were reduced for one of four commercial species. The evidence suggests both gear types can be effective for bycatch reduction, with topless trawls having more extensive supporting research.",
  "action_ids": [
    "2711",
    "2712"
  ]
}

