{
  "query": "What is the evidence for using electropositive deterrents on fishing gear to reduce unwanted catches of sharks and rays?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on nine studies examining electropositive deterrents on fishing gear, the evidence shows mixed results for reducing unwanted catches of sharks and rays. Two of four replicated, controlled studies found that fishing gear fitted with electropositive deterrent materials caught fewer unwanted spiny dogfish, longnose skate, sharks and rays, and fewer undersized halibut, compared to standard fishing gear. However, two other studies and a global systematic review found that electropositive deterrents resulted in similar catches of unwanted spiny dogfish, sharks (total catch), blue shark, and sharks and rays (total catch), compared to gear with no deterrents. Behavioural studies showed that three of four studies found reduced feeding attempts and bait consumption by spiny dogfish, great hammerhead, and draughtboard sharks when deterrent materials were present, though one study found no effect on bonnethead and young lemon sharks.",
  "action_ids": [
    "2696"
  ]
}

