{
  "query": "In European waters, what does the evidence show about the effectiveness of using a square mesh codend instead of a diamond mesh codend for reducing unwanted catch?",
  "relevant_summary": "Evidence from European waters shows that square mesh codends are generally more effective than diamond mesh codends for reducing unwanted catch in trawl nets. In the English Channel, square mesh codends reduced non-commercial unwanted invertebrates in one of two areas compared to diamond mesh codends. When combined with square mesh escape panels, square mesh codends caught fewer unwanted non-commercial invertebrates and reduced numbers of discarded finfish compared to standard trawl nets. A comprehensive review of 26 studies (including multiple European locations such as the English Channel, Mediterranean Sea, Aegean Sea, Adriatic Sea, Bristol Channel, Kattegat and Skagerrak) found that 10 of 16 studies showed square mesh codends reduced unwanted catches of all fish species monitored, young individuals of half or most commercially targeted fish, total unwanted catch (fish and invertebrates), and discarded fish in deeper waters. Studies also found that square mesh codends improved size selectivity for various species including European hake, axillary seabream, poor cod, greater forkbeard, blue whiting, and discarded fish compared to diamond mesh codends.",
  "action_ids": [
    "2714",
    "2136",
    "2138",
    "2724"
