{
  "query": "How does using a square mesh codend compare to rotating a diamond mesh codend for improving size-selectivity in trawl nets?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on 26 studies examining square mesh codends and 6 studies examining rotated diamond mesh codends, both modifications show different effectiveness patterns for improving size-selectivity in trawl nets. Square mesh codends demonstrated improved size selectivity in 6 of 14 studies, showing benefits for species like silver hake, horse mackerel, European hake, and roundfish species, while 5 studies found no difference from diamond mesh for species like Atlantic mackerel and flatfish. The effectiveness varied with fish body shape, generally improving selectivity for roundfish but not flatfish. Rotated diamond mesh (90\u00b0 orientation) showed improved size selectivity in 4 of 6 studies for cod, red mullet, common pandora, and round-bodied species, but no improvement for plaice, annular sea bream, and flatfish. One study found no improvement for cod, plaice and flounder with rotated mesh. Both approaches showed consistent patterns: improved selectivity for round-bodied fish but limited effectiveness for flatfish species. Square mesh codends have been more extensively studied across global fisheries, while rotated diamond mesh research has been conducted primarily in European waters including the Baltic Sea, Kattegat, Skagerrak, Aegean Sea, and North Sea.",
  "action_ids": [
    "2714",
