{
  "query": "How do the effects on fish community composition of prohibiting all commercial fishing compare between the Tasman Sea and the South Atlantic Ocean?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on action document 2667, research shows clear differences in how prohibiting all commercial fishing affects fish community composition between the Tasman Sea and South Atlantic Ocean. In the Tasman Sea, studies found that fish assemblage/species composition was different before and after prohibiting all commercial fishing - one study in an estuary showed changes after two years, and another study in the wider region surrounding two marine reserves found different species composition five years after their creation. In contrast, a study in the South Atlantic Ocean found no change in species composition between a reserve closed to all commercial fishing for 40 years and unprotected fished areas. Similarly, for fish diversity, the South Atlantic study found no difference in overall fish diversity between the 40-year protected area and fished areas, while research from other regions showed varying results. For abundance specifically, the Tasman Sea studies produced mixed findings - one study found most fish species had lower abundance two years after closure compared to before, while another found fish abundance varied over time with some groups higher than others. In the South Atlantic, the research showed higher abundances of one of four commercially targeted fish species in the 40-year protected area compared to fished areas, with another study finding mixed effects on fish densities varying with level of commercial exploitation and higher abundances of five of five commercially exploited species.",
  "action_ids": [
    "2667"
