{"query": "What are the comparative effects of long-term versus temporary fishery closures on marine fish populations?", "summary": "Based on the evidence from multiple studies, temporary and long-term fishery closures show different effects on marine fish populations. Temporary closures (Action ID 2664) showed mixed results with one study finding no increase in cod biomass, survival, or length composition over nine years compared to fished areas, while another study found that during a temporary grouper fishery closure, spear fisher catch numbers of other fish groups (herbivores) increased, indicating they were being targeted more compared to the open season. Catch rates of red mullet and total catch increased after temporary closures in targeted fisheries over 10 years, but European hake showed no change.

Long-term fishery closures (Action ID 2655) demonstrated more consistent positive effects, with studies showing higher weights of young salmon returning to rivers five years after closure in the Norwegian Sea, and higher abundance of some fish species in closed areas compared to open areas after six to eight years. However, effects varied by species with some showing no change or even lower abundance. Long-term closures also reduced unwanted catch of cod and reduced overall fishing effort for lesser sandeel in the North Sea.

Comprehensive marine protected areas with complete fishing prohibition (Action IDs 2224 and 2682) showed the most robust positive effects after 1-25+ years, with 30 of 54 studies finding higher abundances of fish compared to fished areas, while temporary closures showed more variable and often limited benefits. The evidence suggests that long-term closures and permanent no-take zones generally provide more consistent benefits for fish population recovery than temporary closures.", "action_ids": ["2664", "2655", "2224", "2682"]}

