{
  "query": "What are the observed effects of fitting deterrents, such as lights or electropositive materials, to fishing gear?",
  "relevant_summary": "Electropositive materials attached to fishing gear have shown mixed effects on unwanted catch. Some studies found these materials reduced feeding attempts and bait consumption of spiny dogfish, great hammerhead, and draughtboard sharks, while other studies found no reduction in bait consumption by bonnethead and young lemon sharks. Commercially valuable Pacific halibut bait consumption was unaffected. For catch reduction, some studies found electropositive deterrents caught fewer unwanted spiny dogfish, longnose skate, sharks and rays, and fewer undersized halibut, but other studies found similar catches compared to standard gear.\n\nArtificial lights on fishing gear showed more consistent benefits. LED lights on gillnets reduced catches of green turtles and loggerhead turtles compared to nets without lights. In the Adriatic Sea, no loggerhead turtles were caught and died in gillnets with UV lights whereas some did in nets without lights. In shrimp trawl nets, artificial lights fitted to the fishing line (but not to size-sorting grids) caught fewer unwanted fish. However, LED lights on size-sorting grids did not improve size-selectivity for long rough dab, Atlantic cod, haddock and redfish. Longline studies showed mixed effects of increasing light sticks on catching loggerhead and leatherback turtles.",
  "action_ids": [
    "2696",
    "2695",
    "3554"
  ]
}

